    <h3>Using the Pre/postfix Concept With Custom Forms</h3>
    <p>We showed you how to use the prefix and postfix elements on our <a href="#">forms documentation page</a>. You can employ that same techniue here and make custom forms act as your slave to create some very complex forms.</p>

<%= code_example '
<form class="custom">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="large-6 columns">
      <div class="row collapse">
        <div class="large-9 small-9 columns">
          <span class="prefix">mysubdomain</span>
        </div>
        <div class="large-3 small-3 columns">
          <select>
            <option>.com</option>
            <option>.co</option>
            <option>.ca</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="large-6 columns">
      <div class="row collapse">
        <div class="large-10 small-10 columns">
        <select>
          <option>google</option>
          <option>yahoo</option>
          <option>bing</option>
        </select>
        </div>
        <div class="large-2 small-2 columns">
          <span class="postfix">.com</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="row collapse">
    <div class="small-8 columns">
      <select>
        <option>google</option>
        <option>yahoo</option>
        <option>bing</option>
      </select>
    </div>
    <div class="small-4 columns">
      <a href="#" class="button postfix expand">Button</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</form>', :html %>

